snippet.textDisplay:
JAIDENNN, YOU AREN'T ALONE!! I once have been pierced by said hair, and it was not the greatest experience...
For about a month I slept on the couch because I shared a room with my brother, who woke up an hour after me. Instead of being smart, and being ninja quiet every day when I left for school, I decided to just sleep on the couch with earplugs, so I didn't hear my dogs barking to wake me up. One day, I woke up with a bit of a pain in my right ear. I didn't think anything of it, I've had slight pains in my ear in the past, from the plug pushing into my ear canal, but this time felt a bit different. For a week, this tiny twinge in my ear bothered me, slowly getting more and more, and more annoying, until I asked my mom to look in my ear. I thought at first I might have had an ear infection, since my sister had one the week before, so I didnt see it as much of a big deal. But.. it was.
Inside of my ear, my own hair was caught in a curve of my ear, and if I moved my ear a specific way, the hair would TOUCH my ear drum, and cause much agony. My mother who had steady hands, and was skilled in the art of tweezers, used a pair to reach INTO my ear, to get the hair out. Much to BOTH of our suprise, the pointed part of the hair was stuck into the side of my ear canal, and required a bit of clean water and 4% hydrogen peroxide to loosen the skin aroynd it to pull it out. It took two hours of staying completely still so the tweezers wouldn't go into my ear drum, but in the end, she was able to get it out by pulling my ear upward and sqwooshing the bottom of my ear up.
The absolute relief I felt afterward was such a weird feeling, and given that the hair was 2 inches long, was curled around the inside, and actually infected a pore inside of my ear, it was not something I wanted to ever experience again. It was SUPER gross, and for the next week, I cleaned my ear out thourughly with a Q-tip, and never used ear plugs again. Even while I write this, I get PTSD, and my ear twinges, which is also a weird feeling. I can wiggle one singular ear now, so I guess that's a plus.

snippet.textDisplay:
my mom (who had her hair died at least 10 times throughout her life) tried to dye my (brown) hair the purple i had been wanting for a year or so using manic panic, but she didn't want to bleach it so we hoped for the best, but before we even tried to get the stuff on my head something weird happened. The hair dye wouldn't become the violet it was supposed to be, instead it settled on a strange cherry wood/mahogany color, we hoped it would look ok, (sadly) it turned out only a few shades more red, so for probably six months now (in that time my Dad has only let me cut my hair once) i've had this color, and I can't even tell how much of my hair is even dyed anymore since the color was so close in the first place.
And since my mom died in the summer and I've lost my only way to get good dyed hair, i'm gonna have to wait til i'm old enough to drive so i can sneak away and get it done either professionally or by my best friend. which is years from now :(
